icl = calcICL(results,title=title)

Consensus clustering using PAM shows that k=2 has the best clustering stability, with two clean, blue, squares. The other k’s are not as clearly clustered.Other plots show statistics related to consensus cdf and tracking plot. As shown in the item consensus bar graphs, the bars in k=2 were the most similar to each other in height. Consensus Clustering Plus also conveniently shows the heatmaps for each K.

for(gene_count in c(10, 100,1000,10000)){
  mads=apply(matrix_of_data,1,mad)
  d=matrix_of_data[rev(order(mads))[1:gene_count],]
  d=sweep(d,1, apply(d,1,median,na.rm=T))
  title="ConsensusClusterPlus"
  results = ConsensusClusterPlus(d,maxK=6,reps=50,pItem=0.8,pFeature=1,title=title,clusterAlg="pam",distance="pearson")
  #ggplot(results[1], aes(y=Freq, axis1=))
}
end fraction

The p-value for the clustered values are not significantly different than the provided data. This means consensus cluster plus

coldata<-read.csv("coldata.csv",header = T,row.names=1,stringsAsFactors=T)
levels(coldata$dex) <- c(levels(coldata$dex), 2)
coldata$dex[coldata$dex == 'SZ'] <- 2
levels(coldata$dex) <- c(levels(coldata$dex), 1)
coldata$dex[coldata$dex == 'Control'] <- 1

chisq.test(coldata$dex, results1[[2]]$consensusClass)
